00:10:21.479 --> 00:10:29.479
kicked off thinking more about developing with R and what R in the clinical trial space looks like.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:38.679
Thank you. Yeah. Something that you and I had chatted a little bit about before is that you've

00:10:38.919 --> 00:10:45.559
realized people don't want to look at these standard tables, listings, and figures, which

00:10:45.559 --> 00:10:53.640
I just learned that's what TLFs means when I see that listed or named in pharma. But I'm curious,

00:10:55.239 --> 00:11:02.840
in building tools for internal decision making, what has been really helpful for you in

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:10.520
communicating? Yeah. So the fun thing too about the TLF abbreviation is that it goes by many

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:17.400
abbreviations. So watch out for that. It can be TLF, TFL, TLG, TGL. And it all means the same

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:24.599
thing. It was right on top of it in the chat too. And why is it like that? I think that's just to

00:11:24.599 --> 00:11:30.919
confuse people. And I think that's a common theme with abbreviations in clinical trials. So to

00:11:30.919 --> 00:11:38.440
actually answer the question, yeah, a big part of my role is creating visualizations for internal

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:43.559
decision making. And so we think a lot about what is the best way to do that.

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:51.479
I think one of the most important questions is what is the question that someone is trying to

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:58.599
answer and who is the end user? And so, for example, a lot of times the end user for us

00:11:58.679 --> 00:12:05.960
is, say, the executive committee. And so people on the executive committee at Moderna, at least,

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:13.559
are highly skilled professionals. They're not looking for a green button or a red button.

00:12:13.559 --> 00:12:21.799
They want to know what were the results. And they want to see it in a visually pleasing,

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:29.400
straightforward display. But they also still want to know some key statistical elements.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:35.080
And so that's actually part of the reason why a lot of the people on our team have a statistics

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:43.000
background is because we are still displaying confidence intervals and risk ratios in our

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:50.280
displays. And so that's an example where we know the audience and we know the questions they're

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:58.440
going to ask. Another example would be we create, say, visualizations that are going to be used by

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:04.679
the clinical team that want to look at data in an ongoing way. And so you might think about how

00:13:04.679 --> 00:13:10.039
well those people know this data and they want to know every nitty gritty about it.

00:13:10.039 --> 00:13:16.359
And so that's where something like interactive applications really comes into play so that

00:13:16.359 --> 00:13:20.919
as they form their own questions, they can answer those questions.

00:13:21.559 --> 00:13:26.840
That's great. Can you share maybe an example for us or example use case where

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:32.840
people were able to answer some of their own questions with an interactive app?

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:39.799
Sure. So I'm working, one of the big projects that I work on both internally and externally

00:13:39.799 --> 00:13:46.760
right now is on patient profiles. And so the whole goal with patient profiles is that you can

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:54.840
look at one particular participant in a study and the primary uses there is really for safety.

00:13:55.559 --> 00:14:01.960
So you could look at, say, their labs, basic demographics information, their what we call

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:09.239
adverse events, so any safety signals that happen through the study. And so we had a participant

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:19.400
that had an unexpected response in a biomarker. And so they were able to use the patient profile

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:27.000
to look at when that particular biomarker uptick occurred, what else was going on

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:32.200
for that particular participant. Thank you. I think Bill's question maybe

00:14:33.159 --> 00:14:41.559
expands a bit on this. Let's see. Was that visualization, was that a SHINee application?

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:45.640
I think Bill's question was, have you developed SHINee-based apps for your internal users?

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.080
And have you ended up using the same interactive or static visualizations

00:14:51.799 --> 00:14:57.159
in drill downs when interacting with the FDA? Okay. That's like three questions.

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:05.000
Yeah. We can break it up a bit. Yeah. No, that's okay. So much to say here. So

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:15.559
the particular example I provided is actually all being powered by non-SHINee interactivity.

00:15:15.559 --> 00:15:23.320
And there's been a couple of great talks about this topic lately. DeepShaw gave a hilarious talk

00:15:23.400 --> 00:15:31.320
at PositConf about this. And my mentor, Augustine Calatrone, also had a recorded talk at rFarmer

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:38.919
where he kind of touched on this as well. And so kind of with a judicious use of crosstalk,

00:15:38.919 --> 00:15:45.880
plotly, interactive tables, you can make an interactive HTML document

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:56.840
that has a limited but pretty good capabilities. And so that is the current platform for that

00:15:56.840 --> 00:16:03.559
particular patient profile. So yeah, if you're not familiar with that setup, I do think it's powerful.

00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:12.280
In my previous company, we didn't really have a good hosting platform. And so we were able to

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:21.080
really utilize that setup to create interactive reports. Like at a high level, the limitation

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:30.280
is that the interactivity happens on one level, sort of. And there's no recalculation happening

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:36.760
of the data. You're essentially filtering the data. But you can really do a lot with that setup.

00:16:37.479 --> 00:16:44.280
So then moving to like ShinyLin, it's definitely something that our team uses.

00:16:45.479 --> 00:16:53.320
We have a variety of different visualizations. And so that decision is kind of part of

00:16:54.039 --> 00:16:59.400
like what we talked about earlier when you get, say, a data visualization request deciding

00:16:59.400 --> 00:17:06.199
what is the right technology. And so if more and more exploration is the goal,

00:17:06.199 --> 00:17:11.239
then Shiny, I think, is the way to go. And we definitely utilize that.

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:21.400
And then I think the third question is about sending that to the FDA. And that's not something

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:29.719
that we're doing right now. But I think probably a lot of folks are following the R submissions

00:17:29.719 --> 00:17:36.119
group. And they've done a pilot to look at what a Shiny app to the FDA could look like.

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:45.640
And they're going to be doing more utilizing the WebR framework, which is a hot, exciting topic

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:53.800
right now, that could apply really well for this concept of Shiny to FDA as well. Many answers.

