Thank you. Russ, I still had a question in the chat. You want to jump in here next?

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:55.959
Sure, thanks. Similar to you, I wind up sending reports up and stuff. And sometimes the feedback

00:20:55.959 --> 00:21:00.520
that I'll get is good and sometimes like, eh. What's one thing that the leadership does that's

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:06.359
good, that's helpful to you that gets them the report that they actually want?

00:21:07.959 --> 00:21:13.959
Yeah, I love that. So what is good feedback and what is less helpful feedback?

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:33.719
I'm thinking. Good feedback is for them to tell us how and why a report was or wasn't useful

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:44.119
so that we can then apply it to future reports. And so the why I think is important. And maybe

00:21:44.199 --> 00:21:55.719
you have to ask the why. Because if they just say this didn't help, that's not useful. So getting

00:21:55.719 --> 00:22:03.560
a better understanding of what they were looking for, maybe an understanding of a report answers

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:10.839
the question that they asked, hopefully. But if that question changed over time and that's why

00:22:10.839 --> 00:22:18.040
the report is no longer helpful, a little bit of insight into how that question might have changed

00:22:18.599 --> 00:22:26.040
or why that question might have changed helps us kind of predict in the future how questions

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:32.280
might change or how we can provide supplemental materials that might answer those changing

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:42.359
questions. So yeah, I think the takeaway on that is it's OK to turn it into a conversation

00:22:42.359 --> 00:22:48.839
and probe a little bit more so that you can move forward and improve for the future.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:55.079
OK, thank you. Did you have any thoughts you wanted to address?

00:22:57.319 --> 00:23:01.000
I'll just make it really quick. I have a lot of prior careers,

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:05.959
one of which I'm actually a professional counselor with a master's in the whole thing.

00:23:05.959 --> 00:23:10.920
So to me, listening is really, really, really critical. I think it's almost more important

00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:15.000
than the analysis. So just make sure that I really, truly understand what the question is.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:19.560
And if I can give a professional counselor tip for just a second, also find out what it is not.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:24.119
Because when you find out what it is, you might go four miles down that path and find, oh,

00:23:24.119 --> 00:23:28.280
it's actually something slightly different. I was working on that. No, we don't want that.

00:23:28.280 --> 00:23:32.839
Is it this and not that? And once you do that, a lot of things clear up, and then it's easy to

00:23:32.839 --> 00:23:40.040
move forward. Awesome. Yeah, I previously did a lot of work on manuscript writing.

00:23:41.079 --> 00:23:48.439
And so in traditional clinical trials, you have your endpoints that are pre-written,

00:23:48.439 --> 00:23:54.119
and you answer those endpoints that are pre-specified. And sometimes in a more

00:23:54.119 --> 00:24:00.839
exploratory biomarker manuscript setting, there can be a lot of back and forth like

00:24:00.839 --> 00:24:06.439
you're talking about with questions changing over time. And so keeping the conversation

00:24:06.439 --> 00:24:14.040
flowing was always important to really narrow the scope and try to find the answers that they

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:19.959
were looking for. I see a lot of great thoughts on this topic, too, in the chat. I don't know

00:24:19.959 --> 00:24:27.000
if, Catherine, you wanted to share your thoughts here, too. Yeah, I'll kind of repeat what I said

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:35.000
in the chat is one of the things that I learned to ask for is what questions are my leadership

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:40.599
being asked that led them to ask me to do something? Because how they're interpreting

00:24:41.560 --> 00:24:45.640
the questions that they're being asked, and then there's like three levels of information

00:24:45.640 --> 00:24:52.359
distillation before they ask you for a piece of math or a piece of reporting or a visualization.

00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:57.400
And so then you make the thing that you think they were asking for, but it doesn't really

00:24:57.959 --> 00:25:02.040
