00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:39.399
now in my current role, I have a very good mix of statistics, programming, management,

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:46.760
kind of all blended together, which for me works well. I like doing all of those things.

00:52:47.399 --> 00:52:57.399
And like to your a couple of things. So I think we're going to see maybe the definition between

00:52:57.399 --> 00:53:05.879
statisticians and programmers change over time, like where that line is drawn. And that future

00:53:05.879 --> 00:53:13.320
roles might start looking a little bit different. I think there's already several companies that are

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:19.560
kind of calling everyone a data scientist now and blurring those lines. And so I think,

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:27.560
you know, within that idea of blurred lines, it's important to know what you like and advocate for

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:36.120
yourself to do what you like. And then another piece of that, that's something I really like to

00:53:36.120 --> 00:53:43.479
speak about this when I'm interviewing candidates for our team, is to have an open conversation

00:53:43.479 --> 00:53:51.959
about, you know, like you said, I was seeking out this change from a traditional statistician

00:53:51.959 --> 00:53:59.080
to what looks a little bit more like a data scientist, you might say. But like fresh grads,

00:53:59.080 --> 00:54:03.320
to have a conversation about what that means and what that means in terms of your career.

00:54:03.879 --> 00:54:10.439
I always like to have that conversation because the industry as it stands right now

00:54:11.639 --> 00:54:16.520
has more of those traditional roles. And maybe it will change over time, but just kind of having

00:54:16.520 --> 00:54:23.800
an open conversation about it because it might be a new concept for people that are new to the

00:54:23.800 --> 00:54:32.199
industry. Thank you. Yeah. So maybe at some point I'll pull all the answers to these this question

